Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels—Over most of the past decade, central banks have made only limited progress in curbing strong global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Fed has kept interest rates at zero levels while also conducting multiple unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchases.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank also followed the Fed's lead, each implementing their own version of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
But inflation has not received a reasonable increase anywhere.
Although these countries have all been fighting deflationary pressures, their monetary policies—and economic performance—are diverging.
The United States and the United Kingdom now have strong enough growth to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the eurozone and Japan are intensifying QE, pushing long-term policy interest rates further into negative territory.
What accounts for this difference?
A brief answer is debt.
For decades, the United States and the United Kingdom have had current account deficits, making them debtors, while the eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses, making them creditors.
Negative interest rates benefit debtors but not creditors, so the negative rate policy introduced after the global financial crisis stimulated the recovery of the United States and the United Kingdom, but had little effect on the eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
To date, most creditor countries worldwide—countries with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland—have experienced negative interest rates, not only on long-term government bonds and other “risk-free” debt, but also on medium-term bonds.
This is far from a good thing.
Despite the limited effectiveness of low interest rates, the central banks of these economies have remained committed to this policy.
If you argue that QE or lowering interest rates cannot bring economic benefits, they will sidestep the issue and refute the idea that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy—on the surface, this argument seems airtight.
But in reality, this argument is full of loopholes.
Basic economics courses often mention this peculiar phenomenon known as the "backward-bending supply curve of savings": in certain environments, a decrease in interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because the decline in interest rates reduces savers' income, they will cut back on spending, especially if they have savings goals for retirement.
All of this does not negate the general rule—that forms the basis of modern monetary decision-making—that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other spending.
However, the impact varies due to differences in the debt status of the economies.
In a closed economy, every creditor has a debtor, so regardless of what creditors lose due to extremely low interest rates, debtors should benefit.
But in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors will naturally be more numerous than debtors.
For a country with a large amount of foreign debt, the situation is exactly the opposite.
Therefore, the effectiveness of the interest rate floor monetary policy differs between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important, as foreign asset positions were often small (as a percentage of GDP).
However, today, the foreign asset positions of major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, in part because of the leverage that caused the 2007–2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, leverage is still increasing at the national level.
Although the current account imbalances have somewhat eased since the onset of the financial crisis, they have not been reversed.
This implies that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, creating a divergence with deficit economies.
Some commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, have large current account surpluses when oil prices are high, making them notable exceptions to the divergence in foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, the global oil price has plummeted, reversing the wealth trends of these countries.
Their export revenues plummeted—many countries lost half of their wealth—forcing them to run deficits and rely on their massive sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodities boom.
Significant spending cuts are now inevitable.
Industrialized economies face entirely different challenges.
Their problem—somewhat speaking, a matter of luxury—is ensuring that consumers spend the windfall from falling import prices.
However, in creditor countries, negative interest rates seem not to be advancing this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence also exists within the eurozone.
Although as a whole the eurozone is a creditor economy, there are also debtor countries within it.
Debt economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
However, the current account surpluses of traditional debtor countries are too high, leading to a continued increase in the debtor/creditor asymmetry.
What is most noteworthy is that since the outbreak of the financial crisis, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning that the surplus accumulated during this period exceeds the historical total prior to this.
According to the current trend, Germany's creditor position may increase from 60% to 100% of GDP.
Central bank governors should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend of central bank independence precisely because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem to lack patience, struggling greatly with low inflation, even though the output gap is gradually closing, and the U.S. and Japan have achieved full employment.
Debt country central bank governors must stop manipulating the economy with further monetary easing that may be detrimental to production.
In contrast, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of falling oil prices to disappear.
The European Central Bank's president Draghi recently acknowledged that the current monetary policy stance may not be effective in today's global environment.
But promising more of the same old remedy is not the solution.
